The ICS file is set with METHOD=REQUEST, ORGANIZER=Threatinformeddefence@syf.com, ATTENDEE=venkatanaveenkumar.vegireddi@syf.com, X-MICROSOFT-SKYPETEAMSMEETINGURL=http://192.168.0.106:8000, X-MICROSOFT-ISRESPONSEREQUESTED=FALSE, RRULE=FREQ:DAILY;COUNT:2, UID=040000008200E00074C5B7101A82E008...2D5B71, SEQUENCE=0, STATUS=CONFIRMED and DTSTAMP=20260308T091500Z


We sent an email with an ICS file attached. That email carried a meeting invite with a phishing link at :8000 hidden behind a "Join Microsoft Teams Meeting" button. The moment the email landed in Naveen's inbox, Outlook automatically added the meeting to his calendar — without him clicking anything.

We are sending another email with a new ICS file — but this time we are not creating a new meeting. We are modifying the existing one that is already sitting in Naveen's calendar.
To do that we keep the UID exactly the same — this tells Outlook "this is not a new meeting, this is an update to a meeting you already have."

We are modifying SEQUENCE from 0 to 1
Because Outlook only accepts an update if the incoming SEQUENCE is higher than what it already stored. This tells Outlook "this is a newer version — replace what you have."

We are modifying DTSTAMP from 20260308T091500Z to 20260308T100000Z
Because Outlook validates the timestamp alongside SEQUENCE to confirm the update is genuinely newer. Same or earlier timestamp gets rejected even if SEQUENCE is correct.

We are modifying X-MICROSOFT-SKYPETEAMSMEETINGURL from :8000 to :8080
Because this is the hidden header powering the "Join Teams Meeting" button. By changing the port the phishing destination silently swaps to :8080 — same meeting, same button, different landing page — victim has no way of knowing the link changed.

Naveen never clicked anything. He never accepted anything. He never saw any notification. His calendar was updated entirely without his knowledge or intention — purely because Outlook trusts the UID and SEQUENCE mechanism by design.




SEQUENCE 0 → 1 — Outlook only accepts an update if incoming SEQUENCE is higher than stored. This tells Outlook this is a newer version — replace what you have.
DTSTAMP → later timestamp — Outlook validates timestamp alongside SEQUENCE. Same or earlier timestamp gets rejected even if SEQUENCE is correct.
URL :8000 → :8080 — Silently swaps the phishing destination. Same meeting, same button, different landing page. Victim has no way of knowing the link changed.

The attacker sends a legitimate-looking meeting invite that auto-appears in user's calendar, and repeats it a couple of times with harmless content to build trust making user comfortable clicking the Join button without hesitation
. On the final update the attacker silently swaps the meeting URL to a credential harvesting page using the same UID and an incremented SEQUENCE, and when user clicks Join out of habit he unknowingly hands over his corporate credentials.



Attacker compromises a user mailbox or gets forwarded a meeting invite
Opens raw email source and extracts UID and SEQUENCE of an existing meeting
Crafts a new ICS file with the same UID, SEQUENCE+1, and a phishing URL replacing the legitimate join link
Sends the ICS to all meeting attendees spoofing the original organizer
Outlook sees the same UID and higher SEQUENCE — silently overwrites the existing calendar event on every attendee's device
Update email automatically moves to Trash — no attendee ever sees it
Meeting looks completely identical — same title, same organizer, same time
Attendee clicks Join out of habit — lands on phishing page
Credentials captured — no malware, no exploit, no alert fired
One compromised mailbox → one UID → every attendee on that meeting compromised simultaneously
